# Engineering Standards

## 1. Type safety

- **`any` is forbidden.** Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
- **`interface`** for component `Props` and public entity shapes when they are object types (not conditional mapped types).
- **Type-only imports**: `import type { … }` or inline `import { type X }` per ESLint.
- Prefer **`as const` + derived types** over string enums unless interop demands an enum.

## 2. Style & naming

- **4 spaces** indentation; **single quotes**; semicolons; match Prettier output.
- **Arrow functions** for components, hooks, and utilities.
- **Exports**: named exports everywhere **except** Expo Router route files under `src/app/**`, which **must** use `export default` (framework contract).
- **Comments**: `//` for non-obvious _why_ inside functions; JSDoc only on exported contracts that cross module boundaries.

### Components & hooks — explicit types (React Native = same as React)

- **React Native does not change typing**: use the same patterns as React on the web (`react` types apply to `react-native` primitives).
- **Named UI components** (widgets, shared UI, `RootStack`, etc.): either
  `const Title: FunctionComponent<Props> = (props) => { … }` **or**
  `const Title = (props: Props): ReactElement => { … }`
  Always give **props** a named type (`interface` / `type`) when the component accepts props; use `Record<string, never>` (or omit the generic) only for zero-prop leaves.
- **Return type**: prefer an **explicit** `ReactElement` / `ReactNode` (or `FunctionComponent<Props>` which already fixes the return) on anything **exported** or reused — it documents what callers get and catches accidental `undefined` / wrong branches before runtime.
- **Expo Router screens** (`src/app/**` default exports): use **arrow + `export default`**, not `function` declarations, to match the rest of the repo:
  `const HomeScreen = (): ReactElement => { … }; export default HomeScreen;`
- **Custom hooks**: annotate the **return type** when it is not obvious from a single `useQuery` call (e.g. `(): UserQueryResult =>`), or use a named `type` / `interface` for the tuple/object you return.

### Forms (inputs and validation)

- **Single `TextInput` + `useState`** is fine for trivial or one-off fields — no library overhead.
- **When several fields, cross-field rules, dirty/submit state, or reusable schemas matter:** use **`react-hook-form`** with **`@hookform/resolvers/zod`** so validation stays in **Zod**, same as `src/env.ts` and API DTOs.
- **UI wiring:** keep field components and form hooks under **`src/features/<name>/`** (or widgets that compose them); `src/app/**` only mounts the screen.

## 3. Constants & magic values

- No unexplained string/number literals in business logic, navigation labels, or user-visible copy.
- **User-visible copy:** `src/shared/locales/` + `useTranslation` / `t()` — typed via `src/shared/lib/i18n/resources.ts`. See `.cursor/rules/constants.mdc`.
- **Other constants:** `src/shared/lib/constants/`, feature-local `constants.ts`, or `src/store/<domain>/constants.ts` per scope.
- **Query keys:** colocate with the query module under `src/features/...` or `src/hooks/...` as `const queryKeys = { ... } as const`.
- **Magic numbers:** name at use site or extract to the nearest `constants.ts` / shared helper with a short comment only if non-obvious.

## 4. AI readability

- When editing legacy files, preserve local style; do not spread legacy patterns into new files.
- Prefer explicit typed parameters over reading globals or implicit singletons.
